WEBVTT

00:09.700 --> 00:11.266
(FILM CREW CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY)

00:11.333 --> 00:13.333
CREW 1: Okay. We peek through the wall.

00:13.400 --> 00:15.133
Toshiro, camera goes to the porch.

00:15.200 --> 00:17.133
♪ (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

00:17.200 --> 00:19.233
Okay. Let's close the front door.

00:20.666 --> 00:22.166
Clear. Let's stand by to roll.

00:22.233 --> 00:24.200
(CHATTER CONTINUES)

00:24.266 --> 00:26.066
CREW 2: Yeah. That's great.

00:26.133 --> 00:28.700
(BELL RINGS)

00:28.766 --> 00:30.100
♪ (MUSIC STOPS) ♪

00:30.166 --> 00:32.766
All right. Here we go. And action.

00:37.233 --> 00:41.333
♪ (MUSIC RESUMES) ♪

01:04.400 --> 01:06.766
(KEYS JANGLING)

01:28.200 --> 01:29.300
(KNOCKS ON DOOR)

01:35.766 --> 01:38.000
-Wow. -(CHUCKLES)

01:38.066 --> 01:39.566
You don't like it? You like it?

01:39.633 --> 01:42.033
No. It's just, uh-- come in. Come in.

01:45.333 --> 01:46.500
-Hi. -Hi.

01:50.200 --> 01:52.500
-(CHUCKLES) -Hey.

01:56.466 --> 01:58.466
-Okay. Come inside. -(CHUCKLES)

01:59.700 --> 02:01.766
-Is she sleeping? -Yeah. Yeah.

02:02.033 --> 02:03.333
She went down early.

02:03.400 --> 02:05.200
How was bedtime? Was it...

02:05.266 --> 02:06.766
-Um... -You got a new living room.

02:07.033 --> 02:11.433
Yes. Uh, well, the armchair is-- they were-- you know, the...

02:11.500 --> 02:12.500
The Henningsens?

02:12.566 --> 02:15.133
Yeah. Yeah. They were very pretty,

02:15.200 --> 02:17.433
but they weren't really comfortable for watching TV.

02:17.500 --> 02:19.300
You never complained about it before.

02:19.366 --> 02:21.166
Well, I never really got to watch TV before.

02:21.233 --> 02:22.533
Oh.

02:22.600 --> 02:26.466
And the rug it's-- I mean, listen, this is--

02:26.533 --> 02:30.266
it's really, really ugly. (LAUGHS)

02:30.333 --> 02:31.266
You think so?

02:31.333 --> 02:33.333
Oh, my God. Yeah. Look at this couch.

02:33.400 --> 02:34.366
JONATHAN LEVY: What?

02:34.433 --> 02:35.666
It's an affront to the green one.

02:35.733 --> 02:37.266
Look, it's like they're facing off.

02:37.333 --> 02:39.166
JONATHAN: Yeah, well, it's very comfortable, though.

02:39.233 --> 02:41.066
It's hideous. Where'd you get it? IKEA?

02:41.133 --> 02:42.500
Uh, yeah, actually.

02:42.566 --> 02:45.000
-Yeah. But it's cozy. -Now, why didn't you call me?

02:45.066 --> 02:46.500
I would've taken you shopping.

02:46.566 --> 02:48.566
-JONATHAN: I don't know, I... -I mean, I would've even done it myself.

02:48.633 --> 02:50.533
JONATHAN: I don't know. I just took care of it.

02:52.033 --> 02:54.033
So, when'd you do all this with your hair?

02:54.100 --> 02:55.466
MIRA LEVY: Uh, about a week ago.

02:55.533 --> 02:58.166
-JONATHAN: Oh, okay. -Thought Ava would have told you, so...

02:58.233 --> 03:02.000
JONATHAN: No, she's-- Ava's about the most discreet

03:02.066 --> 03:04.100
five-year-old on the planet.

03:04.166 --> 03:05.733
Sometimes it really just breaks my heart,

03:06.000 --> 03:08.066
-how much she holds in. -I know. Yeah.

03:09.066 --> 03:10.733
How was she after school today?

03:12.033 --> 03:14.566
She was fine. Yeah. Nothing unusual. Why?

03:14.633 --> 03:18.033
Oh. Just drop-off was a little tough, you know?

03:18.100 --> 03:20.266
She's-- her stomach hurt, and she cried a little bit.

03:20.733 --> 03:21.733
Hmm.

03:22.000 --> 03:23.766
Did you do drop-off or did Poli?

03:24.033 --> 03:27.533
Me. Poli's away. He left a few days ago.

03:27.600 --> 03:30.433
-Okay. -It's actually easier when he drops her off.

03:32.333 --> 03:33.500
Makes sense.

03:33.566 --> 03:35.266
Yeah. I know.

03:38.566 --> 03:41.200
So, you wanted to talk?

03:42.766 --> 03:43.700
Yeah.

03:43.766 --> 03:46.133
-Okay. Wanna sit in there? -Sure. Yeah.

03:49.666 --> 03:51.066
(JONATHAN CLEARS THROAT)

03:53.433 --> 03:56.600
MIRA: Oh, wow. I didn't know you started this up again.

03:56.666 --> 03:59.133
Oh, what, Shabbat dinner? Yeah.

03:59.200 --> 04:01.366
Uh, yeah, I don't know. It's kind of--

04:01.433 --> 04:04.133
um, my parents came over a few weeks ago for Shabbat,

04:04.200 --> 04:06.266
and Ava really took to it.

04:06.333 --> 04:07.500
-Really? -JONATHAN: Yeah.

04:07.566 --> 04:09.200
-Huh. -JONATHAN: Does that bother you?

04:09.266 --> 04:10.300
No.

04:11.166 --> 04:13.300
I don't think so. (CHUCKLES)

04:13.366 --> 04:15.400
I mean, I think it's been like ten years

04:15.466 --> 04:17.133
-since you've done this. -Yeah, well,

04:17.200 --> 04:19.233
you never really liked it.

04:19.300 --> 04:21.100
You liked that I didn't like it.

04:23.400 --> 04:26.100
I think it's really good for her, actually, you know?

04:26.166 --> 04:28.166
Gives her like a sense of...

04:28.233 --> 04:30.133
structure and a sense of belonging.

04:32.300 --> 04:34.300
Um, you want some?

04:34.366 --> 04:36.200
From Rosenfeld Bagels, it's really good.

04:36.266 --> 04:37.300
MIRA: No, thanks.

04:38.100 --> 04:39.533
I'll take some of that wine.

04:39.600 --> 04:41.000
Yeah. Sure.

04:41.700 --> 04:43.133
(CLEARS THROAT)

04:48.633 --> 04:50.300
(WINE POURING)

04:52.633 --> 04:53.700
-(GLASS CLINKS) -I'll join you.

04:53.766 --> 04:55.033
(CHUCKLES) Okay.

04:56.266 --> 04:57.433
Lechayim.

04:57.500 --> 04:58.766
(SIGHS)

04:59.500 --> 05:00.500
Cheers.

05:00.566 --> 05:02.200
-Eyes. -(SIGHS)

05:19.200 --> 05:20.333
(MIRA CHUCKLES)

05:33.533 --> 05:34.633
So...

05:41.566 --> 05:45.700
So... I've been offered a promotion.

05:48.600 --> 05:51.066
-Congratulations. -MIRA: Thanks.

05:51.133 --> 05:54.566
It's to oversee the, um, European division.

05:54.633 --> 05:56.200
-(CHUCKLES) -Oh. Wow.

05:56.266 --> 05:58.433
MIRA: But I would have to relocate to London.

06:01.066 --> 06:02.700
So, you know, when I got back from Tel Aviv,

06:02.766 --> 06:08.400
Ackerman, he was really happy with, uh, the work I did.

06:08.466 --> 06:10.300
I mean, you know, I did a good job,

06:10.366 --> 06:12.433
just objectively speaking.

06:12.500 --> 06:15.300
Um, so anyway we merged the Tel Aviv office

06:15.366 --> 06:17.600
into the European division and he said,

06:17.666 --> 06:19.733
Ackerman, he was like, "Just take all of Europe."

06:21.166 --> 06:23.166
-Manager in London's leaving. -Okay.

06:25.133 --> 06:27.466
-MIRA: It's a big promotion. -Obviously.

06:27.533 --> 06:29.466
MIRA: It's a lot of money. (CHUCKLES)

06:32.566 --> 06:36.200
So I was hoping that we could, you know,

06:36.266 --> 06:39.266
talk through some ideas and see if we could strategize.

06:39.333 --> 06:40.466
-Strategize? -MIRA: Yeah.

06:40.533 --> 06:42.266
What do you mean? What-- strategize about what?

06:42.333 --> 06:45.066
MIRA: Well, I don't know. That's what I wanted to talk to you about.

06:46.633 --> 06:48.733
But what... (SIGHS)

06:49.000 --> 06:51.733
What did you tell Ackerman? Like, how did you leave it?

06:52.000 --> 06:55.066
I said that it-- you know, I needed to talk to you first.

06:55.133 --> 06:58.133
It was an amazing offer, but, you know,

06:58.200 --> 06:59.433
I needed to talk to you.

07:02.700 --> 07:05.133
Okay. So what are you--

07:05.200 --> 07:07.700
you're thinking that you're gonna go back to...

07:07.766 --> 07:10.533
-flying here every other weekend to see Ava again? -No. No, of course not.

07:10.600 --> 07:12.466
You think that I would actually leave her again?

07:12.533 --> 07:14.200
Oh, all right. All right. So then what?

07:15.300 --> 07:16.366
Taking her with you?

07:17.400 --> 07:19.333
No. No. Not exactly.

07:20.700 --> 07:22.700
Yeah, well, I guess that could be an option if that's...

07:22.766 --> 07:24.566
JONATHAN: No. It's not an option.

07:24.633 --> 07:27.066
It's not an option, so you can forget about that.

07:27.633 --> 07:29.266
(SCOFFS) Unreal.

07:29.333 --> 07:31.666
MIRA: Okay. I didn't say that that's what I wanted to do.

07:31.733 --> 07:34.233
I said I wanted to talk this over together.

07:34.300 --> 07:37.500
So why-- Honey, why are you getting so upset?

07:37.566 --> 07:40.433
This is a-- it's a huge deal, and it's a lot of money.

07:40.500 --> 07:41.700
Money that matters to all of us.

07:41.766 --> 07:43.333
Okay. Will you just stop right there with the money?

07:43.400 --> 07:44.566
MIRA: Well, I don't have a concrete solution.

07:44.633 --> 07:46.033
That's why I was hoping we could hash it out together.

07:46.100 --> 07:47.166
Yeah, of course you don't have a concrete solution

07:47.233 --> 07:48.433
because there is no concrete solution.

07:48.500 --> 07:50.666
So why would you bring it up? Just to see how I'd react?

07:56.766 --> 07:58.000
Okay.

08:00.366 --> 08:01.400
I get it.

08:06.366 --> 08:08.200
Maybe it was a mistake coming here.

08:11.033 --> 08:13.000
I don't know if we can be in the same room yet

08:13.066 --> 08:14.666
without, you know, hurting each other.

08:19.766 --> 08:21.233
(SIGHS)

08:23.266 --> 08:24.333
JONATHAN: What?

08:25.600 --> 08:27.233
What? What are you not telling me?

08:29.166 --> 08:32.566
Mira? I know you.

08:32.633 --> 08:35.366
You wouldn't bring all this up if you didn't have a plan.

08:37.566 --> 08:38.666
What do you want?

08:41.033 --> 08:44.100
I was-- Okay. I was thinking that, um...

08:46.333 --> 08:49.566
maybe the two of you could come to London.

08:50.366 --> 08:52.600
Like, uh, Ava and you.

08:57.100 --> 08:59.000
I thought that could be a possibility.

09:01.300 --> 09:06.400
I mean, you're on, uh, sabbatical this year, right?

09:06.466 --> 09:09.300
So you can write from anywhere. It doesn't have to be here.

09:13.133 --> 09:16.500
I mean, what if you got an apartment nearby?

09:16.566 --> 09:19.133
And we could do shared custody, like we do here.

09:21.366 --> 09:24.433
London's the perfect place for you to write.

09:24.500 --> 09:26.400
There's the libraries and the archives,

09:26.466 --> 09:29.033
-and Oxford's there, so... -(JONATHAN SIGHS)

09:29.100 --> 09:30.733
You know, Horizons would be so happy

09:31.000 --> 09:33.466
to get another apartment and pay for living expenses if I asked them.

09:33.533 --> 09:34.600
Oh, wow. That's very nice of them.

09:34.666 --> 09:36.333
MIRA: Well, it's true. (CHUCKLES)

09:36.400 --> 09:37.466
I mean...

09:40.133 --> 09:42.633
Come on. Aren't you dying to get out of this place?

09:45.333 --> 09:48.100
You're always saying that this country's poisoning you.

09:51.500 --> 09:54.166
And it would be an experience of a lifetime for Ava.

09:55.300 --> 09:59.133
It would be just a great opportunity for her.

09:59.200 --> 10:00.533
You can't deny that.

10:00.600 --> 10:02.400
(SCOFFS) I can't-- I can't believe

10:02.466 --> 10:05.500
you're serious right now. I really can't.

10:07.433 --> 10:09.333
Don't answer me right now. Just think about it.

10:11.200 --> 10:13.133
Just think, like...

10:13.200 --> 10:15.500
you know, we don't have to make a decision this second.

10:15.566 --> 10:16.600
-Just... -Right. Yeah. Yeah.

10:16.666 --> 10:18.133
MIRA: Just, you know, don't rule it out.

10:18.200 --> 10:19.500
-That's all I'm asking you. -Okay, yeah. Don't rule it out.

10:19.566 --> 10:22.100
Of course I'm gonna rule it out. What do you-- what--

10:22.166 --> 10:25.366
what, do you think that we're just like a suitcase

10:25.433 --> 10:27.466
that you can pack up and take with you?

10:27.533 --> 10:29.033
-Wow. -That we're gonna follow you

10:29.100 --> 10:31.166
wherever you feel like going, no matter how disruptive it is

10:31.233 --> 10:33.300
-for Ava and for me? -Okay. Speak for yourself.

10:33.366 --> 10:34.700
I'm sure Ava would be really happy about this.

10:34.766 --> 10:35.733
No, I think I will speak for Ava

10:36.000 --> 10:38.400
'cause obviously somebody needs to.

10:38.466 --> 10:41.333
-Oh, okay. -She just got used to you being back again,

10:41.400 --> 10:43.733
and living in two different houses and all of that.

10:44.000 --> 10:45.433
But it'd be the same there. There'd be two houses there.

10:45.500 --> 10:46.700
-It's not the same. -It's the same schedule there.

10:46.766 --> 10:48.666
Mira, it's not the same. She has a whole world here.

10:48.733 --> 10:50.233
-She has her friends. -MIRA: I-- Okay.

10:50.300 --> 10:52.266
-I know. -And her grandparents, that she's crazy about.

10:52.333 --> 10:54.300
Okay, she could see them over the summer, it's--

10:54.366 --> 10:57.400
She has a whole life here.

10:57.466 --> 10:59.300
-Do you understand that? -Mm-hmm. Yeah.

10:59.366 --> 11:01.133
JONATHAN: A family. A whole community.

11:01.200 --> 11:03.033
-(SCOFFING) Community. -Yes. A commu--

11:03.100 --> 11:04.266
I'm sorry if that word offends you.

11:04.333 --> 11:06.466
I know that you guys live in this global village

11:06.533 --> 11:08.333
where it doesn't matter what you see,

11:08.400 --> 11:10.700
it makes no difference where you go, or any of that.

11:10.766 --> 11:12.500
I'm sorry. Who's "you guys" in this?

11:12.566 --> 11:13.766
-Really? -MIRA: Yeah.

11:15.766 --> 11:17.033
You guys.

11:20.666 --> 11:21.666
(CLEARS THROAT)

11:26.666 --> 11:28.266
(SIGHS, CLEARS THROAT)

11:30.600 --> 11:33.666
(DRAWERS CLATTERING)

11:39.433 --> 11:41.600
MIRA: Here. It was on the cabinet.

11:44.700 --> 11:46.566
JONATHAN: (COUGHS) You know, while we're on the subject,

11:46.633 --> 11:48.433
we should probably start talking a little bit

11:48.500 --> 11:50.166
about the divorce.

11:50.233 --> 11:52.466
(DRAWERS CLATTERING)

11:53.066 --> 11:54.133
Divorce?

11:54.200 --> 11:57.266
Yeah. It just seems like we should start settling things.

11:57.333 --> 11:58.400
Don't you think?

12:01.033 --> 12:03.366
Sure. If it's, uh, important to you.

12:04.700 --> 12:06.566
Uh, we can get it done in a day. It's...

12:06.633 --> 12:07.766
(JONATHAN LAUGHS)

12:08.033 --> 12:09.366
Yeah, I think it's a little more complicated than that.

12:09.433 --> 12:10.733
I'm not sure a day is gonna cut it.

12:11.000 --> 12:12.200
Then a-- a week then.

12:12.266 --> 12:13.633
JONATHAN: Especially if you're planning on traveling soon.

12:13.700 --> 12:14.766
Mm-hmm. Yeah. Sure.

12:15.033 --> 12:16.200
Whatever works for you, Jonathan.

12:16.266 --> 12:17.400
-That's fine. -Okay.

12:20.566 --> 12:22.733
Um, why? Are you-- are thinking about

12:23.000 --> 12:24.733
getting remarried or something?

12:25.000 --> 12:26.400
What? No. No, no, no.

12:26.466 --> 12:29.133
I just think that this state of...

12:29.200 --> 12:31.200
you know, purgatory is just not very healthy for you--

12:31.266 --> 12:33.000
Purgatory? Come on. Don't understate it.

12:33.066 --> 12:36.266
JONATHAN: No, no. I just mean that this... temporary state,

12:37.066 --> 12:39.400
you know, this in-between-ness.

12:39.466 --> 12:40.666
Are you seeing someone?

12:41.266 --> 12:42.333
(CHUCKLES)

12:42.400 --> 12:44.266
What does-- what does that have to do with anything?

12:44.333 --> 12:46.200
MIRA: So you are? (CHUCKLES)

12:47.033 --> 12:48.500
Oh, leave me alone.

12:48.566 --> 12:51.233
What? Why can't you tell me about it?

12:51.300 --> 12:53.166
Because I don't want to.

12:54.200 --> 12:55.266
MIRA: Okay.

12:56.700 --> 12:58.000
JONATHAN: Anyway...

13:00.300 --> 13:01.500
I think, um...

13:06.133 --> 13:07.466
that we'd all benefit...

13:09.500 --> 13:12.333
from having a little more

13:12.400 --> 13:15.100
definition and clarity. Don't you think?

13:15.166 --> 13:16.700
So you decided to kill yourself?

13:16.766 --> 13:17.700
JONATHAN: Oh, come on.

13:17.766 --> 13:20.100
MIRA: When did you start smoking again?

13:20.166 --> 13:21.566
-I don't know. -MIRA: You don't know?

13:21.633 --> 13:24.000
A few months ago. I don't do it that much.

13:24.066 --> 13:25.266
I don't do it in front of Ava.

13:25.333 --> 13:26.666
Fine. Do what you want. I'm not gonna be here

13:26.733 --> 13:28.700
to take you to the ER the next time you have an asthma attack.

13:28.766 --> 13:30.100
I'm not having any attacks.

13:30.166 --> 13:31.700
Can't remember the last time I had one.

13:31.766 --> 13:33.033
MIRA: Okay.

13:38.100 --> 13:40.466
-(RAIN PATTERING DISTANTLY) -(BIRD SINGING)

13:56.300 --> 14:00.566
♪ (GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING ON IPAD) ♪

14:00.633 --> 14:04.433
(RAIN PATTERING CONTINUES)

15:05.666 --> 15:09.233
Everything okay? She's sound asleep?

15:18.233 --> 15:20.000
I didn't know anything about that.

15:21.166 --> 15:22.433
What, the office?

15:23.633 --> 15:26.233
I'm telling you, that kid can really keep a secret.

15:29.566 --> 15:31.266
What's the deal here?

15:31.333 --> 15:33.300
What do you mean?

15:33.366 --> 15:35.366
What's wrong with the bedrooms upstairs?

15:35.433 --> 15:39.233
(LAUGHS) Uh, you know, just...

15:39.300 --> 15:42.233
felt too big up there for us after...

15:42.300 --> 15:45.600
I don't know, the whole house felt too big, and...

15:45.666 --> 15:48.633
And she couldn't really fall asleep on her own,

15:48.700 --> 15:51.266
so she ended up sleeping with me in my bed, and...

15:52.166 --> 15:53.433
when I'd head downstairs to do work,

15:53.500 --> 15:55.200
she would wake up and follow me down.

15:55.266 --> 15:57.533
So it just kind of evolved naturally.

16:01.466 --> 16:03.633
I don't really need a study, you know?

16:03.700 --> 16:06.100
I work in the living room, mostly, so...

16:08.000 --> 16:09.600
What about your privacy?

16:09.666 --> 16:11.700
Well, there's that bookshelf between us.

16:11.766 --> 16:14.466
-It's almost like a wall. -If you have someone over, what do you...

16:15.466 --> 16:18.466
what do you do? I mean, Ava doesn't wake up?

16:18.533 --> 16:22.633
I don't have anyone over when Ava's here. Ever.

16:29.733 --> 16:31.733
-MIRA: Mind if I look? -JONATHAN: Sure.

16:37.466 --> 16:42.066
♪ (QUIET MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

17:24.000 --> 17:25.366
You need anything here?

17:30.300 --> 17:34.300
There's, um, a box there with, uh, some kitchenware

17:34.366 --> 17:36.666
and the china your grandparents gave us.

17:36.733 --> 17:38.233
Yeah. I'm gonna, uh...

17:40.100 --> 17:43.166
I'll, uh, send someone to get it this week.

17:43.433 --> 17:44.533
No rush.

18:06.600 --> 18:08.166
-Are you okay? -MIRA: Yeah.

18:10.700 --> 18:13.666
You know, I-- I think I'm gonna get going.

18:13.733 --> 18:15.466
Do you want anything else to drink?

18:19.200 --> 18:20.366
Maybe a little more wine?

18:22.400 --> 18:23.466
Just a little bit?

18:26.333 --> 18:27.633
-MIRA: Okay. A little. -Okay.

18:27.700 --> 18:29.366
-MIRA: Fine. Yeah. -All right.

18:40.400 --> 18:41.633
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

18:43.600 --> 18:44.633
(MIRA EXHALES)

18:48.366 --> 18:50.166
-Thanks. -JONATHAN: Mm-hmm.

18:51.400 --> 18:53.500
Soon there won't be any trace of me here.

18:57.166 --> 18:58.300
It's fine. It's...

19:00.066 --> 19:02.233
It's totally fine. It's just this, uh...

19:05.033 --> 19:06.633
silly attachment to furniture...

19:09.500 --> 19:11.066
the myth of a home...

19:14.133 --> 19:17.033
and all our dependence on these things. It's...

19:18.200 --> 19:20.266
(EXHALES) That's what keeps fucking everything up.

19:20.333 --> 19:22.700
I mean, it's what fucked it up for us.

19:22.766 --> 19:27.400
You know, being dependent on these objects.

19:27.466 --> 19:28.766
(CHUCKLES)

19:29.033 --> 19:32.300
Yeah, you know, the objects never had

19:32.366 --> 19:34.333
any real significance for me.

19:34.400 --> 19:37.400
Come on. Our whole relationship became an object.

19:37.466 --> 19:40.633
The house, the family...

19:40.700 --> 19:42.400
You know what I mean.

19:45.500 --> 19:46.566
Mm-hmm.

19:48.666 --> 19:51.700
So it's, um-- well, it's not--

19:51.766 --> 19:54.200
-different now for you? -(MIRA CHUCKLES)

19:54.266 --> 20:00.566
You don't feel attached to stuff in your new place?

20:00.633 --> 20:03.533
MIRA: The luxury condo in the Millennium Tower, you mean?

20:03.600 --> 20:06.166
-(LAUGHS) -Whatever.

20:09.666 --> 20:12.300
But yeah, that's my point. I mean, um...

20:15.333 --> 20:19.366
I have no personal attachment to anything there.

20:20.766 --> 20:25.033
I just had a designer furnish the place and then...

20:28.233 --> 20:33.200
But Poli... (EXHALES) It's his dream.

20:33.266 --> 20:36.066
It's his American dream, you know?

20:37.233 --> 20:39.766
Twentieth floor, overlooking the park,

20:41.300 --> 20:42.366
doorman, and all that.

20:42.433 --> 20:46.600
It's amazing how it gives him confidence.

20:48.733 --> 20:50.066
Hmm.

20:53.600 --> 20:55.766
I think I've reached a point in my life

20:56.033 --> 21:00.666
where it doesn't matter where I live anymore.

21:00.733 --> 21:02.266
I mean, there's no place in the world

21:02.333 --> 21:05.133
that would make me feel secure.

21:07.733 --> 21:09.133
I'm sorry to hear that.

21:10.266 --> 21:11.400
MIRA: Don't be.

21:13.466 --> 21:14.533
I'm not sorry.

21:17.300 --> 21:20.500
On the contrary, it's a relief, you know, to--

21:22.300 --> 21:25.400
I mean, there's nothing like that.

21:25.466 --> 21:27.533
Like security, safety.

21:30.566 --> 21:32.200
We thought there was.

21:34.733 --> 21:36.300
We wanted there to be.

21:38.633 --> 21:41.066
But then we turn it into a ritual, you know?

21:41.133 --> 21:43.500
-It was like-- -I know that, like...

21:46.233 --> 21:47.300
I know that you have this need

21:47.366 --> 21:48.733
to diminish everything that we had...

21:49.000 --> 21:50.166
No, I'm not--

21:50.233 --> 21:51.700
-...and justify it. You're-- -Honey, I'm not diminishing it.

21:51.766 --> 21:54.000
No. (LAUGHS) On the--

21:54.066 --> 21:56.333
-Sounds like you are. -No, I'm not. I'm--

21:56.400 --> 22:00.300
I'm just trying to tell you that for me, it was, um--

22:01.200 --> 22:03.266
There was so much denial, you know?

22:04.600 --> 22:07.300
I mean, today, I know. I'm alone. I'm all alone.

22:07.366 --> 22:08.733
Nothing's gonna change that.

22:10.133 --> 22:13.600
It doesn't matter where I am or who I'm with.

22:17.400 --> 22:21.200
-And, um, it's... -(WINE POURING)

22:21.266 --> 22:23.666
...good to understand and make peace with that, you know?

22:23.733 --> 22:26.766
I think it's a-- it's a sign of strength, even.

22:35.000 --> 22:36.066
(JONATHAN EXHALES)

22:36.133 --> 22:37.400
What?

22:37.466 --> 22:39.066
Nothing. I'm listening.

22:43.133 --> 22:45.200
Don't look so worried. I'm fine.

22:46.066 --> 22:47.200
-Are you? -Yes.

22:47.266 --> 22:49.366
-Really? -(LAUGHS) Yes!

22:52.100 --> 22:53.566
-What? -I don't know. I'm just--

22:53.633 --> 22:56.300
I'm, you know, I'm having these flashbacks to...

22:58.066 --> 22:59.633
to your monologues from college.

23:01.733 --> 23:04.766
Every time you and Lucas broke up, you know,

23:05.033 --> 23:10.533
it was always, "Oh, how wonderful it is to acknowledge

23:10.600 --> 23:12.500
that you're actually alone in the world."

23:12.566 --> 23:14.400
I never-- I never said it was wonderful.

23:14.466 --> 23:16.600
JONATHAN: Yeah, but I mean, it was-- it was obviously

23:16.666 --> 23:19.500
a kind of like mania

23:19.566 --> 23:22.133
where you were suppressing all this pain,

23:22.200 --> 23:23.433
but then it would flip to depression

23:23.500 --> 23:24.566
and you'd go running back to him

23:24.633 --> 23:26.300
'cause you couldn't actually be alone.

23:27.533 --> 23:29.066
I mean, it just was so obvious.

23:29.133 --> 23:32.733
It's so obvious that it's a defense mechanism.

23:34.633 --> 23:36.400
Great. (CHUCKLES)

23:38.466 --> 23:41.266
You know, it's pretty insulting when someone uses psychology

23:41.333 --> 23:44.700
to, uh, try and pick apart actual insight

23:44.766 --> 23:46.333
that you've really had.

23:47.466 --> 23:49.600
Can't you just believe that this is how I feel?

23:49.666 --> 23:51.666
I do believe you.

23:51.733 --> 23:53.766
-MIRA: I'm also, you know-- -You're right. I'm sorry.

23:54.033 --> 23:56.200
MIRA: I'm not, um, coming from the same place anymore.

23:56.266 --> 23:58.166
I'm not 20 years old, you know?

23:58.233 --> 23:59.366
JONATHAN: Okay.

24:01.300 --> 24:04.333
What's with all this fucking psychological bullshit anyway?

24:04.400 --> 24:07.266
What, you dating a shrink? (LAUGHS)

24:11.033 --> 24:12.400
I am-- I'm going to one.

24:13.666 --> 24:17.033
Yeah. Not a-- not a shrink. A therapist.

24:18.766 --> 24:20.000
Yeah.

24:21.100 --> 24:23.300
MIRA: You're... You're kidding me.

24:23.366 --> 24:25.766
No, no, no, no. I'm going to one.

24:26.033 --> 24:29.300
Um, I mean, I needed it. And it's, uh--

24:29.366 --> 24:32.100
honestly, it's-- it helped me. It is helping me.

24:33.766 --> 24:35.500
What does it help you with?

24:37.633 --> 24:41.000
JONATHAN: Um, first of all, to understand, you know?

24:41.066 --> 24:43.233
To make sense of everything, of...

24:45.400 --> 24:46.500
of what happened.

24:48.200 --> 24:50.100
-To put it into words. -Yeah.

24:50.166 --> 24:54.566
'Cause I-- I couldn't even begin to comprehend

24:54.633 --> 24:56.266
what had happened.

24:57.666 --> 24:58.766
You know?

25:00.766 --> 25:03.333
Um, she gave me this, uh, exercise to do this thing

25:03.400 --> 25:06.300
called morning pages, where you have to write

25:06.366 --> 25:08.333
three pages, uh, as soon as you get up,

25:08.400 --> 25:11.366
before you've had your coffee, before you've done anything.

25:11.433 --> 25:14.600
Um, you know, first thing that comes into your mind.

25:14.666 --> 25:15.766
Have you heard of that?

25:16.400 --> 25:19.466
Hmm, yeah. Maybe.

25:20.733 --> 25:22.333
(YAWNS) Sorry.

25:23.133 --> 25:24.133
It's okay.

25:25.333 --> 25:27.200
(LAUGHING) I'm so exhausted.

25:27.266 --> 25:29.466
-JONATHAN: Mm. -It's the wine and, um...

25:31.200 --> 25:32.366
I just-- I haven't been sleeping,

25:32.433 --> 25:34.000
you know, since the London offer.

25:34.066 --> 25:36.500
It's just Ackerman's putting so much pressure on me.

25:38.133 --> 25:41.666
Sure. Yeah. That's okay. I get it.

25:41.733 --> 25:44.366
Um, are you okay to drive home?

25:44.433 --> 25:46.100
You sure you don't want any coffee?

25:46.166 --> 25:47.300
Wait. You were in the middle of something.

25:47.366 --> 25:49.533
No, it's okay. It's all right. It's all good.

25:51.233 --> 25:52.633
-MIRA: Wh-- -So espresso, right?

25:52.700 --> 25:54.033
MIRA: Hey!

25:55.266 --> 25:57.100
Please don't make a big deal out of this.

25:57.166 --> 25:58.400
It has nothing to do with anything.

25:58.466 --> 26:00.500
It's just-- I wanna hear about it.

26:00.566 --> 26:02.533
It's just my-- I'm so-- I'm so tired.

26:02.600 --> 26:03.633
It's my exhaustion.

26:03.700 --> 26:05.233
No. No. Look, nothing happened. Everything's okay.

26:05.300 --> 26:07.133
MIRA: But I wanted-- I want you to finish

26:07.200 --> 26:08.366
what you were telling me, please.

26:08.433 --> 26:10.300
I mean, maybe you could read it to me.

26:10.366 --> 26:11.466
JONATHAN: Read what?

26:11.533 --> 26:13.633
The morning papers, I think...

26:13.700 --> 26:15.566
Morning pages. No. No, no, the-- (SCOFFS)

26:15.633 --> 26:18.166
The whole point's that you're not supposed to show anybody.

26:18.233 --> 26:21.366
Well, but you can just-- you can read it to me, okay?

26:21.433 --> 26:23.200
And I won't tell anyone that you did, okay?

26:23.266 --> 26:24.233
Here you go.

26:24.300 --> 26:25.633
(SIGHS) I don't want coffee.

26:29.333 --> 26:31.700
-Read to me, please. -JONATHAN: Why-- (SIGHS)

26:31.766 --> 26:33.566
Why is this so important to you?

26:36.100 --> 26:37.300
You're important to me.

26:40.600 --> 26:42.400
I-- I could just go get it.

26:42.466 --> 26:44.233
No. Okay, okay. Fine.

26:47.300 --> 26:48.600
-I'll get it. -Thank you.

26:54.266 --> 26:55.500
(JONATHAN CLEARS THROAT)

27:10.466 --> 27:12.166
I'm not sure there's much of a chance

27:12.233 --> 27:15.166
-I can read my own handwriting. -(MIRA CHUCKLES)

27:15.233 --> 27:17.433
Maybe I'll read you something that I wrote this morning.

27:17.500 --> 27:19.133
I can still kind of remember it.

27:26.000 --> 27:27.300
(CLEARS THROAT)

27:27.733 --> 27:28.733
Okay.

27:33.166 --> 27:35.533
It's written in the third person.

27:35.600 --> 27:38.266
I don't know why it came out like that. It just did.

27:38.333 --> 27:40.233
The whole point is that you're just supposed to...

27:40.733 --> 27:42.500
to go with the flow.

27:44.566 --> 27:46.233
Okay. Um... (CLEARS THROAT)

27:46.300 --> 27:50.700
"Apparently, his obsessive rational thinking

27:50.766 --> 27:55.733
at that age was only compensation

27:56.000 --> 27:58.533
for all the anxieties.

27:58.600 --> 28:02.433
Because there was the father, this dominant father

28:02.500 --> 28:05.033
casting a shadow over him,

28:05.100 --> 28:09.166
judgmental, with strict moral codes,

28:09.233 --> 28:11.633
and he--" Meaning me.

28:11.700 --> 28:12.666
MIRA: Mm.

28:12.733 --> 28:16.133
Uh, "Tried so hard to please this father,

28:16.200 --> 28:18.366
to live up to his standards,

28:18.433 --> 28:20.533
but he always felt like he'd failed,

28:20.600 --> 28:25.566
so that, gradually, he developed this permanent feeling

28:25.633 --> 28:31.066
of 'I'm not good enough, I'm not moral enough,

28:31.133 --> 28:33.300
I'm too egocentric,'

28:33.366 --> 28:35.433
which, in the world he grew up in,

28:35.500 --> 28:37.300
is the worst possible sin.

28:40.200 --> 28:42.700
And on the other hand, there was the mother,

28:42.766 --> 28:46.733
who was always too weak to face down this tough father.

28:47.000 --> 28:49.300
But she was such an anxious person herself

28:49.366 --> 28:53.600
that even with her, this boy, he couldn't really be himself,

28:53.666 --> 28:56.033
he couldn't share his hardships, his fears,

28:56.100 --> 28:59.266
because she'd immediately get so overwhelmed

28:59.333 --> 29:02.333
that her anxiety would only compound his.

29:02.400 --> 29:05.366
And then, when he realized no one actually saw him,

29:05.433 --> 29:07.433
his true self that is,

29:07.500 --> 29:11.200
no one could help him cope with everything he was going through,

29:11.266 --> 29:14.000
he fell deeper and deeper into himself,

29:14.066 --> 29:17.000
and kept all of his pain and anxiety inside,

29:17.066 --> 29:19.166
and never told anyone anything,

29:19.233 --> 29:21.233
and this split inside him

29:21.300 --> 29:24.133
wouldn't let him truly be in a relationship,

29:24.200 --> 29:26.466
because there was always part of him that he kept hidden,

29:27.300 --> 29:29.000
he was never fully present,

29:30.100 --> 29:31.266
until Mira showed up.

29:33.366 --> 29:37.366
And to a certain extent, she saved him by seeing him.

29:37.433 --> 29:41.233
For the first time in his life, he felt like he might be pulled

29:41.300 --> 29:43.566
out of the inherent loneliness.

29:46.400 --> 29:50.700
But only after she left did he realize how,

29:50.766 --> 29:55.400
even with her, he was there-not-there,

29:55.466 --> 29:58.100
and how hard it must have been to live with this,

29:58.166 --> 30:01.266
with someone who was always partly somewhere else,

30:01.333 --> 30:03.366
inside his own head,

30:03.433 --> 30:07.266
how that could make her feel lonely and unseen.

30:07.333 --> 30:11.766
And this realization helped him deal with her leaving him,

30:12.466 --> 30:14.466
to make sense of it,

30:14.533 --> 30:16.533
and that disabused him of the idea

30:16.600 --> 30:21.233
that he'd been a victim of some kind of sudden cataclysm."

30:22.400 --> 30:26.466
♪ (QUIET MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

31:18.066 --> 31:21.300
(BOTH BREATHING HEAVILY)

31:41.200 --> 31:44.066
(MOANING)

31:55.500 --> 31:56.766
Oh, fuck.

32:00.200 --> 32:01.533
(BREATHES HEAVILY) Stop.

32:01.600 --> 32:03.633
-This isn't good. -What?

32:04.400 --> 32:05.533
It's not good.

32:07.466 --> 32:10.333
I don't-- I don't want this. I don't wanna sleep with you.

32:11.566 --> 32:13.066
It's not good for me.

32:15.366 --> 32:18.166
It took me a really long time to get where I am right now.

32:18.233 --> 32:19.300
I don't wanna...

32:20.333 --> 32:23.033
I don't want to go back to that fucking torment.

32:25.266 --> 32:26.366
No.

32:27.333 --> 32:28.700
I just don't...

32:35.766 --> 32:37.500
I don't think you actually really understand

32:37.566 --> 32:39.600
what it was like for me here a year ago.

32:41.566 --> 32:45.733
I wanna know. Tell me. Tell me.

32:47.033 --> 32:48.600
-Do you really? -Yes.

32:56.466 --> 32:58.100
That first moment, I was...

33:01.633 --> 33:03.100
I was just on autopilot.

33:05.433 --> 33:09.333
I woke Ava up, I got her dressed,

33:09.400 --> 33:10.766
I dropped her off at preschool,

33:11.033 --> 33:14.066
and I canceled all my classes, and then I came back home.

33:16.500 --> 33:21.033
And I thought I was literally losing my mind.

33:25.133 --> 33:27.333
Then there was a moment where I thought

33:27.400 --> 33:31.466
that I didn't even want to stay alive.

33:34.200 --> 33:35.733
There was lots of moments where I was sure

33:36.000 --> 33:37.633
I didn't want you to stay alive.

33:39.533 --> 33:41.533
Like, I really wanted you to die.

33:45.766 --> 33:50.733
And then there was...

33:52.766 --> 33:56.366
-there was a moment when I wanted Ava to die. -(EXHALES)

34:01.200 --> 34:02.733
For that to be my revenge.

34:04.300 --> 34:07.566
And then that night, she started coughing like crazy.

34:09.566 --> 34:12.000
And at one point, she threw up from coughing so much.

34:12.066 --> 34:15.033
And then she spiked a fever of 104

34:15.100 --> 34:18.500
and I wasn't sure if I should take her to the emergency room.

34:18.566 --> 34:21.300
That's why I ended up putting her in a bathtub.

34:21.366 --> 34:25.433
And that lasted all night, and I was scared to death.

34:27.000 --> 34:28.333
I thought I'd killed her.

34:34.666 --> 34:39.000
And it took three days for the antibiotics to kick in.

34:39.066 --> 34:40.766
And that was a nightmare, but it was also the best thing

34:41.033 --> 34:43.766
that could happen to me because I didn't have

34:44.033 --> 34:47.500
a second to myself, I barely slept.

34:47.566 --> 34:50.633
And then you came back on the weekend

34:50.700 --> 34:52.633
and you took her and...

34:52.700 --> 34:55.733
her fever was already gone by then.

34:56.000 --> 34:59.300
I was-- and I was alone all of a sudden.

35:01.500 --> 35:04.466
But I was already in a more human state.

35:07.000 --> 35:08.266
I could breathe by then.

35:09.700 --> 35:13.266
(EXHALES) And start some kind of healing.

35:15.266 --> 35:18.600
Then a few minutes would go by and I wouldn't think about it.

35:21.466 --> 35:23.033
Think about you.

35:25.133 --> 35:26.533
Then a few hours.

35:30.233 --> 35:33.700
Now, I'll go half a day without thinking about it.

35:35.666 --> 35:40.000
Sometimes the whole day, especially when Ava's here.

35:43.300 --> 35:46.533
So, yeah, no way I'm going back to that.

35:48.066 --> 35:50.533
You know, we'll have sex and it'll be amazing,

35:50.600 --> 35:53.300
and then it's all the way back to the bottom.

35:56.000 --> 35:57.100
No way.

36:02.366 --> 36:05.166
What makes you think it was any different for me?

36:07.166 --> 36:09.266
-Oh, Mira. -(SOBS)

36:11.666 --> 36:13.633
It was a nightmare for me too.

36:18.233 --> 36:20.200
I couldn't stop thinking about you.

36:21.066 --> 36:22.500
Not even for a second.

36:23.566 --> 36:25.033
I just, uh...

36:29.333 --> 36:31.600
Please don't-- please don't do that.

36:33.000 --> 36:34.300
Don't do what?

36:36.366 --> 36:37.666
-(SNIFFLES) -Don't.

36:39.366 --> 36:42.100
Don't say things you don't mean

36:42.166 --> 36:45.066
just to prove that we're in the same boat, 'cause we're not.

36:45.733 --> 36:47.200
But how would you know?

36:51.000 --> 36:52.666
I just miss you all the time.

36:56.566 --> 36:59.466
I never stopped loving you, not even for a second.

37:05.166 --> 37:06.700
I never stopped wanting you.

37:12.433 --> 37:14.233
I want you now so bad.

37:17.300 --> 37:20.233
This whole past week, I come just thinking about you.

37:25.766 --> 37:26.766
Hold on.

37:34.666 --> 37:38.366
Sweetie, stop. Please. Please. No.

37:38.433 --> 37:39.533
I'm sorry.

37:46.000 --> 37:47.000
I'm sorry.

37:48.133 --> 37:49.133
It's okay.

38:09.300 --> 38:11.300
Do you want me to go now? (SNIFFLES)

38:27.600 --> 38:28.600
Thanks.

38:31.466 --> 38:34.300
You sure I can't get you any coffee or anything?

38:34.366 --> 38:35.433
No? Okay.

38:37.733 --> 38:38.766
(SIGHS)

38:53.566 --> 38:56.033
What time are you picking up Ava?

38:56.100 --> 38:57.600
Uh, in the morning, around 10:00.

38:57.666 --> 38:58.733
Okay.

38:59.000 --> 39:01.233
You'll have her bag ready for school on Monday?

39:01.300 --> 39:02.400
JONATHAN: Of course.

39:05.000 --> 39:06.100
Okay.

39:15.000 --> 39:18.500
If Poli wasn't coming, would that change anything for you?

39:20.166 --> 39:21.166
What?

39:23.500 --> 39:25.333
MIRA: If I was going to London alone...

39:28.266 --> 39:30.166
would you consider coming with Ava?

39:32.233 --> 39:35.400
♪ (MUSIC PLAYING ON IPAD) ♪

39:36.533 --> 39:38.600
What's Poli have to do with anything?

39:42.533 --> 39:43.600
All right.

39:52.166 --> 39:54.666
(WINDCHIME TINKLING)

40:07.133 --> 40:08.466
MIRA: I can't drive right now.

40:09.766 --> 40:13.566
Stay here tonight, okay? Okay?

40:29.433 --> 40:32.500
♪ (MUSIC PLAYING ON IPAD) ♪

40:35.366 --> 40:40.566
♪ (GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

41:02.400 --> 41:04.366
JONATHAN: I got some shirts. Do you want one?

41:05.166 --> 41:06.166
Thank you.

41:11.366 --> 41:13.566
-Will you help me? -JONATHAN: Yeah.

41:13.633 --> 41:18.700
♪ (GENTLE MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

42:00.133 --> 42:02.400
(CHUCKLING)

42:30.066 --> 42:33.500
(RAIN PATTERING ON IPAD)

42:49.533 --> 42:52.266
-(PHONE CHIMES) -JONATHAN: Shit, sorry.

43:02.266 --> 43:05.100
-Is that your girlfriend? -(CHUCKLES)

43:07.100 --> 43:08.533
I wouldn't go that far.

43:10.333 --> 43:12.600
-(WHISPERING) Your lover? -(CHUCKLES)

43:16.466 --> 43:19.000
Did you tell her that I was coming over tonight?

43:22.233 --> 43:23.200
Yes.

43:23.266 --> 43:24.766
(PHONE VIBRATES)

43:28.333 --> 43:30.000
Just try to ignore it.

43:33.433 --> 43:35.066
(PHONE VIBRATES)

43:36.166 --> 43:37.700
She's not giving up. That's dedication.

43:43.633 --> 43:45.233
(PHONE VIBRATES)

43:50.166 --> 43:52.133
Sorry. I'll just turn it off.

43:56.433 --> 43:58.300
Just give me one second, okay?

44:06.266 --> 44:07.366
Hey.

44:07.433 --> 44:09.700
(LAURA SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY OVER PHONE)

44:09.766 --> 44:11.533
Good. Uh, yeah, but listen,

44:11.600 --> 44:14.133
it's not cool to, like, bombard me with...

44:14.200 --> 44:16.666
LAURA:  Because you were supposed to call me.

44:16.733 --> 44:18.666
I told you, I'd call you when she left.

44:18.733 --> 44:20.600
LAURA:  Oh, so she hasn't gone yet?

44:20.666 --> 44:23.633
No, she hasn't. She's still here, okay?

44:23.700 --> 44:25.633
(LAURA SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

44:25.700 --> 44:27.266
JONATHAN: She's-- she's in bed.

44:30.266 --> 44:31.400
My bed.

44:32.266 --> 44:34.500
Listen. Laura? Laura?

44:34.566 --> 44:36.200
We-- we need to talk, 'cause this is--

44:36.266 --> 44:37.733
this is really just not, uh...

44:40.633 --> 44:43.033
Okay, well what I'm saying is that we should take a break

44:43.100 --> 44:44.033
because this is just not--

44:44.100 --> 44:46.033
not working out for me right now.

44:49.000 --> 44:51.133
Not a, uh, uh-- I wouldn't--

44:54.233 --> 44:56.666
Okay, you know, let me just-- let me stop you here

44:56.733 --> 44:59.133
before you say something that you're gonna regret.

45:04.033 --> 45:07.300
Look, I'm-- I'm really sorry it has to end like this.

45:07.366 --> 45:11.533
But, uh, honestly, I've been feeling for a while that--

45:11.600 --> 45:14.000
well, you know, that...

45:14.066 --> 45:16.333
-(LAURA SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY) -JONATHAN: I'm not...

45:19.566 --> 45:22.300
-Okay, bye. -(MIRA SIGHS)

45:29.566 --> 45:31.766
-Sorry about that. -It's okay.

45:32.033 --> 45:34.600
I just couldn't help overhearing it.

45:34.666 --> 45:38.300
Yeah, I wasn't really trying so hard

45:38.366 --> 45:40.000
to make sure you didn't.

45:44.133 --> 45:45.500
Why'd you get out of bed?

46:00.600 --> 46:02.133
Did that upset you?

46:02.700 --> 46:04.400
No, of course not.

46:07.400 --> 46:09.300
Why'd you tell her I was in the bed with you?

46:11.633 --> 46:13.366
-Why? -Yeah.

46:13.433 --> 46:16.500
I don't know. I didn't really feel

46:16.566 --> 46:18.566
like I needed to hide it.

46:18.633 --> 46:20.233
But you had plans with her tonight

46:20.300 --> 46:22.066
and you knew it was gonna upset her.

46:25.533 --> 46:26.633
Okay.

46:29.133 --> 46:30.100
(SIGHS)

46:30.166 --> 46:33.700
Mira, um, I'm sorry that that happened that way.

46:33.766 --> 46:35.200
Can we forget about it?

46:37.400 --> 46:38.500
Okay?

46:46.100 --> 46:48.633
-What? -(LAUGHING) Nothing.

46:48.700 --> 46:50.666
I don't-- It's just a shame.

46:50.733 --> 46:52.766
It sounded pretty serious, right?

46:54.633 --> 46:56.166
I don't know, I mean, anyway,

46:56.233 --> 46:57.766
it's not really relevant anymore, is it?

46:59.466 --> 47:03.066
I don't know about that. I mean, it's not unforgivable,

47:03.133 --> 47:05.200
so I'm-- I'm sure she'll understand.

47:14.466 --> 47:15.466
Fuck.

47:20.233 --> 47:21.666
(SIGHS)

47:24.600 --> 47:26.700
You haven't lost your talent for saying the wrong thing

47:26.766 --> 47:29.433
at the wrong time, that's-- that's for sure.

47:32.033 --> 47:36.300
It's just I, uh, felt a little sad, you know?

47:36.366 --> 47:37.733
-I felt sad for you. -Yeah. Oh, that's sweet.

47:38.000 --> 47:39.166
How about you snap out of it, okay?

47:39.233 --> 47:40.500
'Cause you're not my couples counselor.

47:40.566 --> 47:42.366
Well, I just think it's a shame to give up on something

47:42.433 --> 47:44.166
-over a couple texts-- -JONATHAN: Enough!

47:45.266 --> 47:46.266
Enough!

48:00.666 --> 48:03.066
Can I just say something to you, Mira?

48:03.433 --> 48:04.533
Truthfully...

48:06.000 --> 48:10.633
I'm not buying your whole "ode to solitude" thing.

48:10.700 --> 48:12.566
Okay? It's bullshit.

48:13.700 --> 48:16.000
And I don't believe that you believe in it.

48:17.166 --> 48:21.033
It's a weakness. It's fear. It's not strength.

48:21.100 --> 48:24.333
And I don't know what's gonna happen to you if you can't--

48:24.400 --> 48:26.533
I'm not-- I'm not trying to be patronizing,

48:26.600 --> 48:31.033
but I can see that your chaos and your detachment--

48:31.100 --> 48:33.766
your total detachment and...

48:42.066 --> 48:45.233
I remember how-- how we were back then

48:45.300 --> 48:47.166
before we moved in together

48:48.066 --> 48:50.066
and what we saved ourselves from.

48:52.600 --> 48:55.400
How we pulled each other out of exactly--

48:55.466 --> 48:59.033
exactly that loneliness that you're talking about.

49:00.566 --> 49:05.200
It wasn't an illusion, and you know it.

49:09.233 --> 49:10.500
It was a miracle.

49:10.566 --> 49:13.500
It was like the biggest miracle of our lives.

49:18.300 --> 49:20.366
And we're just like throwing it all away.

49:22.333 --> 49:24.600
And it's... it's...

49:26.333 --> 49:28.466
It's just, like, it's a terrible mistake.

49:28.533 --> 49:31.066
It's terrible. And...

49:31.133 --> 49:33.533
We should-- I don't know.

49:33.600 --> 49:35.666
We should've just done everything we could to...

49:37.533 --> 49:38.600
to...

49:40.500 --> 49:42.433
save it, to not just give up.

49:49.400 --> 49:51.033
I can't, uh...

49:54.600 --> 49:56.366
I don't know how to...

50:00.266 --> 50:01.533
(GROANS)

50:04.000 --> 50:05.366
I'm really nauseous.

50:12.766 --> 50:14.766
Something is fucked up with me.

50:19.233 --> 50:21.500
Something inside is so fucked up.

50:36.600 --> 50:38.000
(SIGHS)

50:43.366 --> 50:44.700
Can I play you something?

50:47.333 --> 50:48.466
MIRA: Play something?

50:49.433 --> 50:51.200
Yeah. It's...

50:51.266 --> 50:53.300
It's a voicemail I got this morning.

50:55.733 --> 50:57.300
Just hold on a second.

51:01.033 --> 51:02.766
POLI: (ON PHONE) Hey, Jonathan. It's Poli.

51:03.033 --> 51:05.366
Um, I'm in the airport right now,

51:05.433 --> 51:07.400
I'm going for a week, so, uh...

51:08.133 --> 51:09.700
uh, listen...

51:09.766 --> 51:13.333
I know that Mira is going to meet you tonight, okay?

51:13.400 --> 51:15.566
I don't know what you're going to do together.

51:15.633 --> 51:18.600
It's a free country, you're still married,

51:18.666 --> 51:20.533
legally, so...

51:21.600 --> 51:23.400
(LAUGHS)  I'm just saying,

51:23.466 --> 51:26.100
this whole fucking situation here...

51:26.166 --> 51:30.233
The suspicions and, uh, the fights and all that...

51:30.300 --> 51:32.600
It-- it's just not for me.

51:32.666 --> 51:35.333
You two sit together, talk,

51:35.400 --> 51:37.600
decide what you wanna do with each other.

51:37.666 --> 51:39.400
I had enough.

51:39.466 --> 51:42.366
Uh, if she wants to come back to you, believe me,

51:42.433 --> 51:45.566
I'm the last person to stop her, okay?

51:45.633 --> 51:47.766
And you can share this with Mira if you want.

51:48.033 --> 51:50.600
She probably told you everything anyway, so...

51:50.666 --> 51:53.200
-just, uh, keep me posted. -Ava. Hey!

51:53.266 --> 51:55.466
-Hi, babe! -Where's Poli?

51:56.400 --> 51:58.633
Poli? Um... Poli's not here.

51:58.700 --> 52:00.466
We're at Daddy's house, honey.

52:00.533 --> 52:03.233
But I'm hungry, and I want Poli to make me pancakes.

52:03.300 --> 52:04.766
Sweetie, we don't eat in the middle of the night.

52:05.033 --> 52:07.200
-Okay? Come here. -But Poli lets me.

52:07.266 --> 52:09.000
JONATHAN: Yeah? Does he?

52:09.066 --> 52:10.533
Well, you know what? Let's go lay down

52:10.600 --> 52:12.000
and we'll try to sleep,

52:12.066 --> 52:14.000
and if you're still hungry, we'll make a snack. Okay, honey?

52:15.066 --> 52:16.000
All right?

52:16.066 --> 52:18.266
But can I sleep in your bed, Mommy?

52:19.466 --> 52:22.133
Oh, my... Tomorrow you can.

52:23.366 --> 52:25.433
-Promise, tomorrow. -Come on. Let's go lie down.

52:25.500 --> 52:27.133
I'll lie down next to you, all right?

52:27.200 --> 52:28.733
Come give Mommy a big good night kiss.

52:29.766 --> 52:31.000
Love you.

52:31.066 --> 52:32.433
All right. Let's go.

52:33.466 --> 52:34.666
One second, all right?

52:34.733 --> 52:36.066
MIRA: Sure.

52:36.133 --> 52:40.000
JONATHAN: Yeah, just... There we go.

52:40.066 --> 52:41.366
All right.

52:42.700 --> 52:45.133
'Bout I sing you a little dream song?

52:48.200 --> 52:50.033
AVA LEVY: I don't wanna go to sleep yet.

52:50.100 --> 52:51.566
JONATHAN: Of course you don't wanna go to sleep yet.

52:51.633 --> 52:53.200
We're not gonna go to sleep, okay?

52:53.266 --> 52:54.600
I'm just gonna sing a song.

52:55.300 --> 52:57.066
-Okay. -Stay awake.

